{{Infobox royalty | name = Anne Christine of Sulzbach | image = AnnaChristineSulzbSavoy.jpg | succession = [[Princess of Piedmont]] | reign = 15 March 1722 &ndash; 12 March 1723 | reign-type = Tenure | birth_date = {{Birth date|1704|2|5|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Sulzbach-Rosenberg|Palace of Sulzbach-Rosenberg]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1723|3|12|1704|2|5|df=y}} | death_place = [[Royal Palace of Turin]], Turin | spouse = [[Charles Emmanuel III of Sardinia|Charles Emmanuel of Savoy, Prince of Piedmont]] | house = [[House of Wittelsbach|Wittelsbach]] | burial_place = [[Basilica of Superga]], Turin, Italy | father = [[Theodore Eustace, Count Palatine of Sulzbach]] | mother = [[Eleonore Maria Amalie of Hesse-Rheinfels|Maria Eleonore of Hesse-Rotenburg]] | issue = [[Prince Vittorio Amedeo Theodore of Savoy]]}}
'''Anne Christine of Sulzbach, Princess of Piedmont''' (Anne ''Christine'' Louise; 5 February 1704 &ndash; 12 March 1723), also called '''Christine of the Palatinate''', was a princess of the [[Bavarian Circle]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and first wife of [[Charles Emmanuel III of Sardinia|Charles Emmanuel of Savoy, Prince of Piedmont]], heir to the throne of the kingdom of Sardinia. She died during childbirth at the age of 19.
==Biography== Anne Christine Louise was born a [[Count Palatine|Countess Palatine]] of [[Sulzbach-Rosenberg|Sulzbach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genealogics.org/getperson.php?personID=I00022589&tree=LEO|title=Pfalzgräfin Anna Christiane Luise von Sulzbach|accessdate=1 December 2009|last=Pas|first=Leo van de|work=Genealogics.org}}</ref> She was the daughter of [[Theodore Eustace, Count Palatine of Sulzbach|Theodore Eustace, Prince Palatine of Sulzbach]] (1659–1732), the head of a Roman Catholic [[cadet branch]] of Bavaria's [[Wittelsbach]] dynasty, and [[Eleonore Maria Amalie of Hesse-Rheinfels|Princess Eleonore of Hesse-Rheinfels-Rotenburg]] (1675-1720), daughter of [[William, Landgrave of Hesse-Rotenburg]].<ref name="huberty">{{cite book | title=’’L'Allemagne Dynastique, Tome IV – Wittelsbach’’ | publisher=Laballery |author1=Huberty, Michel |author2=Giraud, Alain |author3=Magdelaine, F. and B. | year=1985 | location=France | pages=82, 141, 166, 202, 273, 310–311| isbn=2-901138-04-7}}</ref> Her parents had married in 1692, Anne Christine being their eighth child.<ref name="huberty"/>
Christine's older brother [[John Christian, Count Palatine of Sulzbach|John Christian]] (1700-1733) succeeded their father as Prince Palatine, also becoming [[Margrave]] ''[[jure uxoris]]'' of [[Bergen op Zoom|Berg-op-Zoom]]: His son, [[Charles Theodore, Elector of Bavaria]], was the last of the senior branch of the House of Wittelsbach.<ref name="huberty"/> Her older sister [[Countess Palatine Francisca Christina of Sulzbach|Francisca Christina]] became [[Prince-Abbot|Princes-Abbess]] of [[Thorn Abbey|Thorn]] and, later, of the more important [[Imperial immediacy|immediate]] convent of [[Essen Abbey|Essen]].<ref name="huberty"/> Christine was a first cousin of her husband's subsequent wife [[Polyxena of Hesse-Rotenburg|Polyxena of Hesse, Queen consort of Sardinia]], of [[Landgravine Caroline of Hesse-Rotenburg|Caroline of Hesse, Princess de Condé]], and of [[Landgravine Christine Henriette of Hesse-Rotenburg|Christine of Hesse, Princess di Carignano]].<ref name="huberty"/>
On 15 March 1722 at [[Vercelli]], she married Charles Emmanuel of [[House of Savoy|Savoy]], [[Prince of Piedmont]] and later [[King of Sardinia]] as [[Charles Emmanuel III]]. He was the second son of [[Victor Amadeus II]], Duke of Savoy, King of Sardinia and [[Anne Marie d'Orléans]] and had been heir apparent to the Savoyard throne since 1715 at the death of [[Victor Amadeus, Prince of Piedmont]]. The following year, she gave birth to a son who was created the [[Duke of Aosta]]. She died a few days later on 12 March 1723 at the age of nineteen in Turin. Her only child died in 1725 in his second year, thus she left no direct descendants. She was buried at [[Turin Cathedral]] and was moved to the [[Basilica of Superga]] in Turin in 1786. {{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
==Issue== * [[Prince Vittorio Amedeo Theodore of Savoy]] (7 March 1723 &ndash; 11 August 1725), died in infancy; buried at Superga.
